</div></section></section><section aria-label=3D"Article content"><section =
class=3D"body main-article-body"><section class=3D"abstract" id=3D"abstract=
1"><h2 data-anchor-id=3D"abstract1"><a id=3D"abstract1-anchor" data-anchor-=
id=3D"abstract1" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>Abstract</h2>
<p>The term =E2=80=98nutrient density=E2=80=99 for foods/beverages has been=
 used loosely to promote the Dietary Guidelines for Americans. The 2010 Die=
tary Guidelines for Americans defined =E2=80=98all vegetables, fruits, whol=
e grains, fat-free or low-fat milk and milk products, seafood, lean meats a=
nd poultry, eggs, beans and peas (legumes), and nuts and seeds that are pre=
pared without added solid fats, added sugars, and sodium=E2=80=99 as nutrie=
nt dense. The 2010 Dietary Guidelines for Americans further states that nut=
rient-dense foods and beverages provide vitamins, minerals and other substa=
nces that may have positive health effects with relatively few (kilo)calori=
es or kilojoules. Finally, the definition states nutrients and other benefi=
cial substances have not been =E2=80=98diluted=E2=80=99 by the addition of =
energy from added solid fats, added sugars or by the solid fats naturally p=
resent in the food. However, the Dietary Guidelines Advisory Committee and =
other scientists have failed to clearly define =E2=80=98nutrient density=E2=
=80=99 or to provide criteria or indices that specify cut-offs for foods th=
at are nutrient dense. Today, =E2=80=98nutrient density=E2=80=99 is a ubiqu=
itous term used in the scientific literature, policy documents, marketing s=
trategies and consumer messaging. However, the term remains ambiguous witho=
ut a definitive or universal definition. Classifying or ranking foods accor=
ding to their nutritional content is known as nutrient profiling. The goal =
of the present commentary is to address the research gaps that still exist =
before there can be a consensus on how best to define nutrient density, hig=
hlight the situation in the USA and relate this to wider, international eff=
orts in nutrient profiling.</p>
<section id=3D"kwd-group1" class=3D"kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong=
> Nutrient density, Healthy eating, Dietary Guidelines for Americans</p></s=
ection></section><hr class=3D"headless">
<p>=E2=80=98Nutrient-dense foods=E2=80=99 are widely recommended; however, =
there is no consistent definition of what distinguishes a nutrient-dense fo=
od. There is also little understanding of how individual nutrient-dense foo=
ds fit into healthful dietary patterns. The purpose of this commentary is t=
o discuss how nutrient-dense foods have been defined and address some of th=
e caveats of existing definitions. The commentary also relates the challeng=
es of defining nutrient density to recent efforts at nutrient profiling.</p=
>
<p>The 2005 Dietary Guidelines Advisory Committee placed a major emphasis o=
n the selection of nutrient-dense foods, which were defined as =E2=80=98tho=
se foods that provide substantial amounts of vitamins and minerals and rela=
tively few calories=E2=80=99<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref1" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref1" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>1</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Conversely, non-nutrient-dense foods were foods that were def=
ined as supplying energy but relatively small amounts of micronutrients. Co=
nsumption of nutrient-dense foods was endorsed by the 2005<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and 2010<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> Dietary Guidelines for Americans (DGA). However, neither the 2=
005<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> nor the 2010 DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> actually defined the terms =E2=80=98nutrient dense=E2=80=99 or=
 =E2=80=98nutrient density=E2=80=99; rather, both listed food groups which =
they deemed =E2=80=98nutrient dense=E2=80=99: whole grains, fruit, vegetabl=
es, fat-free or low-fat milk and milk products, seafood, lean meats and pou=
ltry, eggs, beans and peas, and nuts and seeds, prepared without added fats=
 or sugars<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. The implication was that these foods were healthful and other=
s were not. Neither the 2005<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> nor the 2010 DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> made an effort to use a more useful method of categorizing the=
 nutrients that foods contributed at the expense of their SFA, added sugars=
 or Na content.</p>
<p>Nutrient profiling of foods is the science of ranking foods based on nut=
rient composition. The algorithms used to profile foods generate a numerica=
l score which can then be used to help consumers make healthier choices<sup=
>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref7" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref7" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>7</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, influence regulatory issues<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref8" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref8" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>8</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref9" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref9" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>9</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, help consumers rate foods using front-of-package labels or la=
bels on store shelves<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref10" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref10" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>10</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref11" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref11" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>11</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, define healthy foods that can be advertised to children<sup>(=
</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref12" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref12" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>12</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref15" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref15" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>15</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and motivate industry to develop more healthful foods<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref15" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref15" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>15</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/=
#tab1" class=3D"usa-link">Table 1</a> shows a sample of the variety of nutr=
ient density algorithms that have been used. The continuous systems that ge=
nerate scores calculate and assign a score to each food item, which can the=
n be used to rank and compare foods. There is no score or scoring system th=
at identifies an individual food as =E2=80=98nutrient dense=E2=80=99; foods=
 are only nutrient dense in comparison with other foods. The criteria used =
in nutrient profiling systems are not currently regulated and not all algor=
ithms have been validated.
</p>
<section class=3D"tw xbox font-sm" id=3D"tab1"><h2 class=3D"obj_head">Table=
 1.</h2>
<div class=3D"caption p"><p>Summary of selected nutrient profile models</p>=
</div>
