<div class=3D"tw-foot p"><div class=3D"fn" id=3D"fn1"><p>RDA, Recommended D=
ietary Allowance; DV, Daily Value; ED, energy density; RDI, Reference Daily=
 Intake; LIM, limit; RACC, Reference Amount Customarily Consumed; MRV, maxi=
mum recommended value; HEI, Healthy Eating Index; CHO, carbohydrates.</p></=
div></div></section><section id=3D"sec1"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-a=
nchor-id=3D"sec1"><a id=3D"sec1-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"sec1" class=3D"us=
a-anchor"></a>Unanswered questions and challenges in defining nutrient-dens=
e foods</h2>
<p>There are many unanswered questions and challenges relating to the devel=
opment of a scientific definition of nutrient density and the application o=
f this term<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref16" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref16" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>16</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref18" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref18" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>18</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Many of the questions surrounding the definitions of nutrient=
 density were identified in a Practice Paper of the Academy of Nutrition an=
d Dietetics<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref17" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref17" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>17</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and by Scarborough <em>et al.</em>
<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref18" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref18" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>18</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. The DGA=E2=80=99s all-encompassing definition of nutrient-den=
se foods<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> also adds to these challenges/questions. Using these published=
 references, herein we focus on eight of the important challenges related t=
o defining nutrient density. We expand and explain these important challeng=
es; highlight the situation in the USA; and relate the concept of defining =
nutrient density and its challenges to wider international efforts in nutri=
ent profiling.</p>
<section id=3D"sec1-1"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">1. What units of measure=
 should be used to determine nutrient density?</h3>
<p>It seems to be accepted that nutrient density refers to nutrients compar=
ed with kilocalories (or kilojoules), but should other measures also be con=
sidered or used in place of kilocalories/kilojoules? A number of standard =
=E2=80=98units=E2=80=99 have been used in the calculation of nutrient densi=
ty scores, including 418 kJ (100 kcal), the Reference Amount Customarily Co=
nsumed (RACC) and 100 g. Scarborough <em>et al.</em>
<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref18" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref18" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>18</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> stated that 100 g is commonly used in nutrient profiling; howe=
ver, those authors pointed out the caveat that if the food was high in a nu=
trient if 100 g were consumed, what would happen if that food (for example,=
 mustard) was not customarily consumed in that amount? Similarly, 418 kJ (1=
00 kcal) may also be an implausible serving for some foods, especially fres=
h vegetables with no fat added, and consumers who consume a standard servin=
g size may not understand that they are not getting as many nutrients as th=
ey think. Ultimately, the decision on what units to use may need to reflect=
 how a nutrient profiling system will be used; if consumers are introduced =
to 418 kJ (100 kcal) or the MyPlate serving size<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref19" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref19" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>19</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> it might be the easiest for them to understand. Use of MyPlate=
 serving sizes would also send a consistent message to the US public; howev=
er, these servings are often inconsistent with RACC servings and these serv=
ing sizes may not apply worldwide.</p></section><section id=3D"sec1-2"><h3 =
class=3D"pmc_sec_title">2. What (and how many) nutrients should be included=
 in algorithms that assess nutrient density?</h3>
<p>The specific nutrients and the number of nutrients that should be used i=
n determining the nutrient density of a food have been debated<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref6" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref6" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>6</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref20" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref20" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>20</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>; and although the selection of nutrients is arbitrary<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, many models use similar nutrients. In general, however, the n=
utrients chosen for determination of nutrient density scores have included =
those that have been identified as shortfall nutrients, such as dietary fib=
re, Ca and vitamins A, C and E<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>; and as nutrients to limit, including total fat, SFA, <em>tran=
s</em>-fat, cholesterol, total and added sugars, and Na<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref6" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref6" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>6</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref21" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref21" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>21</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref26" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref26" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>26</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and, often, protein. Protein is included in many models, not b=
ecause it is a shortfall nutrient or a nutrient to limit in the diets of mo=
st Americans<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref27" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref27" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>27</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, but because of its importance in the diet. Several models use=
 other nutrients<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref6" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref6" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>6</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref21" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref21" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>21</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref26" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref26" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>26</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>; however, this overall approach suggests that some nutrients m=
ay not be =E2=80=98as important=E2=80=99 in contributing to diet quality or=
 to overall health promotion and disease reduction.</p>
<p>A bigger problem is that selection of nutrients for nutrient profiling s=
uggests that nutrients not generally used in scoring may not be =E2=80=98as=
 important=E2=80=99 or do not contribute to overall health promotion and di=
sease reduction. An example of this is K, which is seldom included in nutri=
ent profiling, although it has been identified as a nutrient of public heal=
th concern because of its inverse relationship with blood pressure<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>As another example, fruit and vegetables have been defined as nutrient-d=
ense foods<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. The importance of many fruit and vegetables for health promot=
ion and disease prevention is related not only to their dietary fibre and m=
icronutrient content, but also to their phytochemical content<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref28" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref28" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>28</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref31" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref31" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>31</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Phytochemicals have been shown to have a wide array of health=
 benefits, including reducing inflammation associated with diabetes<sup>(</=
sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref28" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref28" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>28</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> or other chronic diet-related illnesses such as CHD<sup>(</sup=
>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref29" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref29" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>29</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and osteoprotective<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref30" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref30" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>30</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> or neuroprotective effects<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref31" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref31" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>31</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. If the nutrient density score does not consider these compone=
nts, then fruits and vegetables may be undervalued.</p>
<p>Several algorithms use only nutrients to limit to determine the nutrient=
 density of a food. One of these has traditionally been SFA; however, since=
 new information suggests that some dietary SFA do not play a role in influ=
encing circulating LDL-cholesterol levels, and subsequently the risk of CVD=
<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref32" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref32" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>32</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, should SFA be included as a nutrient to limit? Further, the r=
ole of SFA must be examined in light of macronutrient substitutions made wh=
en SFA is reduced in the diet =E2=80=93 notably addition of other solid fat=
s or sugars<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref33" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref33" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>33</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. <em>Trans</em>-fats, while shown to be associated with increa=
sed risk of CVD<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref34" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref34" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>34</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, are not in the US Department of Agriculture Nutrient Database=
<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, so it is difficult to include them in some of the algorithms.=
 The rapid elimination of <em>trans</em>-fats from processed foods in the U=
SA and many other countries also questions their current public health impo=
rtance and their role in a nutrient density algorithm. Cholesterol intake h=
as a recommended limit of no more than 300 mg/d, and it is seldom included =
in nutrient density algorithms; in part, because dietary cholesterol has on=
ly a tenuous link to serum cholesterol levels<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref36" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref36" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>36</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>The levels of selected nutrients to define nutrient density are also amb=
iguous. The words =E2=80=98substantial=E2=80=99 for amounts of vitamins and=
 minerals and =E2=80=98few calories=E2=80=99 (or kJ) used by the DGA are va=
gue, and without definition, not only for scientists but also consumers. Th=
e best estimate for =E2=80=98substantial amounts of vitamins and minerals=
=E2=80=99 comes from the US Food and Drug Administration=E2=80=99s criteria=
 for foods that can be considered for a health claim. These foods must prov=
ide &gt;10 % of the Daily Value (DV) of protein, dietary fibre, vitamin A, =
vitamin C, Ca or Fe per RACC, prior to supplementation, and less than 13 g =
of total fat, 4 g of SFA, 60 mg of cholesterol or 480 mg of Na per RACC<sup=
>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref37" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref37" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>37</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. The concept of =E2=80=98relatively few calories=E2=80=99 has =
no reference standard at all.</p>
<p>Whether the nutrients considered in defining nutrient density should be =
country specific is another question. Nutrients that were identified in the=
 (2005) DGA as low in the diets of US populations were Ca, K, dietary fibre=
, Mg, vitamins A, C and E for adults; Ca, K, dietary fibre, Mg and vitamin =
E for children and adolescents; vitamin B<sub>12</sub>, Fe, folic acid and =
vitamins E and D for specific populations<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. But the 2010 DGA identified dietary fibre, Ca, vitamin D and =
K as nutrients of public health concern for children and adults, and others=
 as nutrients of concern for sub-populations<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Are these nutrients shortfall nutrients in other countries? A=
nd even within the USA, would updates to DGA mean that new nutrient density=
 algorithms would need to be developed every five years? If fortificants ar=
e added to the food supply, would these nutrients remain shortfall nutrient=
s?</p>
<p>The question of how many nutrients are required to make a food nutrient =
dense also remains unanswered. For example, is a food that contains high am=
ounts of one or two nutrients any less nutrient dense than a food that cont=
ains moderate amounts of several vitamins and minerals?</p></section><secti=
on id=3D"sec1-3"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">3. Are foods that are high in =
shortfall nutrients, but also contain nutrients to limit (e.g. SFA and <em>=
trans-</em>fat, total fat, cholesterol, Na and added sugars), nutrient dens=
e?</h3>
<p>The majority of algorithms used to determine nutrient density include nu=
trients to limit (<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282=
407/#tab1" class=3D"usa-link">Table 1</a>); however, there is no standard d=
efinition of =E2=80=98nutrient to limit=E2=80=99 or the number to include, =
which is reflected in <a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1=
0282407/#tab1" class=3D"usa-link">Table 1</a>. There are also potential pro=
blems with adding too many nutrients to the formulas, in that nutrient dens=
ity can decrease with too many nutrients in the algorithms<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref6" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref6" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>6</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>Here, we give four examples of foods that are high in both shortfall nut=
rients and nutrients to limit, using the Weighted Nutrient Density Score (W=
NDS) to illustrate inconsistencies in defining nutrient-dense foods. The WN=
DS is one algorithm that models nutrient density; it uses eight nutrients (=
all capped at 100 % of the DV) and explains 65 % of the variance in Healthy=
 Eating Index (HEI)<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref38" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref38" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>38</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> scores<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. To increase the variation by only 1 % (to 66 %), three additi=
onal nutrients =E2=80=93 vitamin D, K and folate =E2=80=93 would need to be=
 added. Although this is only one such algorithm to assess nutrient density=
, it can be used to standardize the examples presented.</p>
<section id=3D"sec1-3-1"><h4 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">Example 1</h4>
<p>Poultry without skin has been specifically designated by the DGA as a nu=
trient-dense food; however, poultry with skin has not been. Why? Poultry sk=
in clearly affects the nutrient density of chicken calculated using the WND=
S: chicken leg with skin (WNDS ~18), without skin (WNDS 25=C2=B75). However=
, the fatty acid composition of poultry skin comprises primarily unsaturate=
d fatty acids, not SFA. Chicken skin (per ounce (~28 g)) has 3=C2=B74 g of =
SFA, 5=C2=B74 g of MUFA and 2=C2=B75 g of PUFA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Has poultry with skin been designated as a =E2=80=98non-nutri=
ent-dense=E2=80=99 food because of the total fat content, which ignores the=
 beneficial MUFA and PUFA; the relatively low SFA content; or because of th=
e energy (548 kJ (131 kcal)/ounce (~28 g))<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> it adds to the food? There is no reason given in the DGA. By i=
tself, poultry skin would have a near-perfect score of 10 in the fatty acid=
 ratio subcomponent of the HEI-2010. Since the term =E2=80=98relatively few=
 calories (kJ)=E2=80=99 required for a nutrient-dense food is undefined, it=
 is unclear if poultry skin fits into this category.</p></section><section =
id=3D"sec1-3-2"><h4 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">Example 2</h4>
<p>The score for whole-wheat bread is higher (WNDS 41=C2=B71) than that for=
 white bread (WNDS 9=C2=B75), with dietary fibre being the likely nutrient =
driving the score. So, using this criterion, whole-wheat bread is more nutr=
ient dense than white bread; however, if other nutrients such as Fe, thiami=
n and folate were used in the calculation of nutrient density, would the nu=
trient density scores have been different? Whole-wheat bread is recommended=
 by MyPlate<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref19" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref19" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>19</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and is a =E2=80=98Go=E2=80=99 food in the National Heart, Lung=
, and Blood Institute=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98We Can=E2=80=99 list of foods<sup>=
(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref39" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref39" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>39</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Consumption of whole-grain products has been associated with =
better diet quality and health biomarkers<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref40" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref40" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>40</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref41" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref41" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>41</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, but because they may not be fortified as refined-grain produc=
ts are, they may not provide the nutrient profile that refined grains do.</=
p></section><section id=3D"sec1-3-3"><h4 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">Example 3<=
/h4>
<p>The 2005 DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref2" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref2" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>2</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and the 2010 DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> clearly state that nutrient-dense foods do not contain added f=
ats or sugars: =E2=80=98Selecting lower-fat forms of foods in each food gro=
up and forms free of added sugars=E2=80=94in other words nutrient dense ver=
sions of foods=E2=80=94provides individuals a way to meet their nutrient ne=
eds while avoiding the over-consumption of (kilo)calories and of nutrients =
such as SFA=E2=80=99. Does this definition mean that foods such as pre-swee=
tened (PS) fortified ready-to-eat cereals (RTEC), low-fat flavoured milk an=
d fruited low-fat yoghurt are not nutrient dense? The effect that nutrients=
 to limit has on the calculated nutrient density is striking; for example, =
added sugars changes the nutrient density of Cheerios<sup>=C2=AE</sup> (WND=
S 49=C2=B75) to that of Frosted Cheerios<sup>=C2=AE</sup> (WNDS 11=C2=B73).=
 Both types of cereal are fortified with important nutrients: vitamins A, C=
, D, B<sub>6</sub> and B<sub>12</sub>, thiamin, riboflavin, niacin, Ca, Fe =
and Zn. Should both types of cereal be considered nutrient dense? We think =
so. Consumption of any type of RTEC has also been associated with consumpti=
on of milk<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref42" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref42" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>42</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, which provides additional nutrients, including three of publi=
c health concern (vitamin D, Ca and K)<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, as well as protein, riboflavin, vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and P.=
 Both RTEC and PSRTEC have been associated with improved diet quality, diet=
ary adequacy, lower weight and better cardiovascular risk profiles<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref43" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref43" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>43</sup>
</a>
<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref48" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref48" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>48</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, suggesting that the amount of sugar added to PSRTEC is not de=
trimental to diet quality, dietary adequacy or overall health risk. Further=
, consumption of PSRTEC by children has not been associated with intakes of=
 added sugars over the Institute of Medicine=E2=80=99s recommendation (CE O=
=E2=80=99Neil, T Nicklas and VL Fulgoni, unpublished results). Most RTEC, i=
ncluding PSRTEC, are also low in SFA and Na. Thus, should PSRTEC be conside=
red nutrient dense by virtue of their micronutrient fortification, and low =
fat and Na content, despite their added sugars? The authors believe =E2=80=
=98yes=E2=80=99, despite the results of the algorithm and the recommendatio=
n by the 2010 DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. It is also important to note that many individuals add sugar =
to RTEC, with less control and precision than when PSRTEC are prepared; thu=
s, added sugars in RTEC may actually be higher than those seen in some PSRT=
EC.</p></section><section id=3D"sec1-3-4"><h4 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">Examp=
le 4</h4>
<p>Similarly, low-fat chocolate milk and fruited low-fat yoghurt have added=
 sugars, but should these foods be considered nutrient dense by virtue of t=
heir nutrient contribution to the total diet? The nutrient density score of=
 chocolate milk varies with the amount of SFA in the product. Whole milk-ba=
sed chocolate milk has a WNDS score of =E2=88=923=C2=B71, whereas a skimmed=
 milk-based chocolate milk has a WNDS score of 31=C2=B73 (compared with 54=
=C2=B773 for skimmed white milk). Skimmed milk-based chocolate milk has vir=
tually no SFA; however, an 8-ounce (~237 ml) serving has 15=C2=B75 g of add=
ed sugars and 165 mg of Na (6=C2=B79 % DV)<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Does the presence of added sugars and the high Na content neg=
ate the fact that chocolate milk also provides &gt;10 % of the DV for prote=
in, Ca, P, K, riboflavin, pantothenic acid and vitamins A, D and B<sub>12</=
sub>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>(35)</sup>
</a>? High levels of three nutrients of public health concern, identified a=
bove, are present in chocolate milk and contribute to the nutrient intake o=
f children<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref49" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref49" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>49</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref50" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref50" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>50</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Further, consumption of chocolate milk has not been negativel=
y associated with weight in children<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref50" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref50" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>50</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. If children will not drink recommended amounts of plain milk,=
 but will drink chocolate milk, should the added sugars content deter healt=
h professionals from recommending it because it is not =E2=80=98nutrient de=
nse=E2=80=99? A similar argument could be made for non-fat fruited yoghurt =
with added sugar or vegetables served with Ranch Dressing<sup>=C2=AE</sup>.=
 By the DGA definition, foods like low-fat chocolate milk, fruit yoghurt or=
 vegetables with dressing that contain added fats or sugars are not nutrien=
t dense. The DGA definition of nutrient-dense foods needs to be revisited.<=
/p></section></section><section id=3D"sec1-4"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">4=
. Should all foods within a specific food group designated by the Dietary G=
uidelines for Americans as nutrient dense actually be considered as nutrien=
t dense?</h3>
<p>The DGA has =E2=80=98awarded=E2=80=99 nutrient dense status to all fruit=
, vegetables, lean meats, poultry without skin, beans, non-fat/low-fat milk=
 products and whole/enriched grain products by fiat<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. But foods within a group can show considerable heterogeneity =
in nutrient content. Many questions revolve around the nutrient density of =
fruit and vegetables; and these questions result from the lack of definitio=
n of nutrient density. Some vegetables (e.g. iceberg lettuce, celery, mushr=
ooms and courgettes) have a high water content and contain few vitamins and=
 minerals, but they are low in energy and contain some fibre<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. This leads to another question: should there be distinctions =
in nutrient density within the fruit and vegetable groups to be consistent =
with the distinctions in the other food groups, i.e. refined <em>v</em>. wh=
ole grains?</p>
<p>Fruit and vegetables vary widely in their nutrient density scores. For f=
ruit, the WNDS<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> ranges from 3=C2=B75 for dried cranberries to 204 for raw blac=
kberries. Does this imply that dried fruits are not healthful? Dried fruit =
is a rich source of nutrients<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and its consumption has been associated with better diet quali=
ty and reduced levels of obesity in the USA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref51" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref51" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>51</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Although data are limited, there also appears to be a clear e=
ffect that processing or preparation has on the nutrient density of a given=
 food; for example, the WNDS of an apple is 66, of unsweetened apple sauce =
is 36 and of 100 % apple juice is 21.</p>
<p>The WNDS<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref5" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref5" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>5</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> for vegetables ranges from approximately 35 for cooked corn to=
 287 for raw endive, chicory, escarole or romaine lettuce. The WNDS for let=
tuce, celery and mushrooms is 148, 146 and 103, respectively. By comparison=
, raw spinach has a WNDS of 216. Although across-method comparisons cannot =
be made, within-method comparison of scores suggests that while lettuce, ce=
lery and mushrooms are not as nutrient dense as raw spinach, they have reas=
onably high nutrient density scores, when compared with some non-plant food=
s. Scores may have been higher if phytochemicals had been included; for exa=
mple, iceberg lettuce and celery have some lutein + zeaxanthin, but raw spi=
nach has very high levels of phytochemicals<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Many mushrooms have =CE=B2-glucans and phenolic compounds tha=
t provide health benefits; those mushrooms that have been irradiated are hi=
gh in vitamin D, a nutrient of public health concern<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref52" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref52" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>52</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. How can these important components of these foods be captured=
 in the currently available algorithms to determine nutrient density? The g=
radation in nutrient density among vegetables suggests that it is important=
 to follow MyPlate=E2=80=99s recommendation for variety in vegetable select=
ion<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref19" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref19" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>19</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>; although it is not clear the extent to which both inter- and =
intra-variety is needed.</p>
<p>Nuts are another example. Nuts are considered by the DGA to be nutrient =
dense, but one serving (1 ounce (~28 g)) of cashew nuts has an SFA content =
of 14 %, which exceeds the =E2=80=98recommendation=E2=80=99 for SFA of &lt;=
10 % of energy recommended for the total diet<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Macadamia nuts, Brazil nuts and some varieties of pine nuts a=
re also relatively high in SFA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Does this mean that these nuts are not nutrient dense and can=
not be included in an overall healthy diet? Do all foods need to contribute=
 less than 10 % of energy from SFA or can the whole diet be balanced? No it=
 doesn=E2=80=99t; consumers of tree nuts have consistently been shown to ha=
ve better nutrient intake profiles, diet quality, lower weight and better h=
ealth risk markers than non-consumers<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref53" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref53" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>53</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref54" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref54" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>54</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p></section><section id=3D"sec1-5"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_titl=
e">5. Should definitions for nutrient density consider the bioavailability =
of nutrients by food source?</h3>
<p>Bioavailability of nutrients and its effect on nutrient density are near=
ly impossible to determine. For example, 418 kJ (100 kcal) of raw spinach (=
432 g) has 431 mg Ca, more than the 359 mg Ca in 418 kJ (100 kcal) of non-f=
at milk (293=C2=B78 g)<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref35" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref35" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>35</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. But while the 418 kJ (100 kcal) of non-fat milk is a reasonab=
le serving size (1=C2=B72 cups; although not that promulgated by MyPlate), =
418 kJ (100 kcal) of raw spinach is not (61 cups). Also, some plant foods, =
like spinach, contain high concentrations of indigestible salts, such as ox=
alic acid, which is a potent inhibitor of Ca. Thus, mean Ca absorption from=
 spinach is only 5 % compared with a mean of 27 % from milk ingested at a =
=E2=80=98similar load=E2=80=99<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref55" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref55" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>55</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. However, the oxalate content of spinach varies widely (400=E2=
=80=93900 mg/100 g fresh weight) among samples<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref56" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref56" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>56</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, which would alter interference with absorption in the spinach=
 in different samples.</p>
<p>The same argument can be made for Fe; the non-haem Fe found in spinach (=
11=C2=B779 g/418 kJ (100 kcal) =E2=80=93 an implausible intake) is not as b=
ioavailable as the haem Fe found in meat. Moreover, the overall efficiency =
of Fe absorption is linked to the Fe status of the individual; if someone i=
s Fe deficient, he/she will absorb more Fe. Absorption of non-haem Fe is al=
so influenced by other foods consumed; for example, vitamin C increases abs=
orption of non-haem Fe, as does concomitant consumption of foods with haem =
Fe. These physiological variations, both in the animal and plant foods and =
in the absorption potential by consumers, make it virtually impossible to i=
nclude the bioavailability of nutrients in foods in any consideration of a =
nutrient density algorithm, although they are extremely important.</p></sec=
tion><section id=3D"sec1-6"><h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">6. Should nutrient =
density be defined differently for naturally nutrient dense foods <em>v.</e=
m> fortified nutrient dense foods?</h3>
<p>With few exceptions, such as supplemental crystalline vitamin B<sub>12</=
sub> for those over 50 years of age, the DGA<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> recommends that nutrients come from foods. So, should nutrient=
 density be defined differently for fortified foods? Many foods in the USA =
are micronutrient fortified, for example those made with enriched flour, as=
 mandated by law. Other foods are not fortified by law but as a public heal=
th measure, for example iodized salt; and yet other foods, such as RTEC, ar=
e nutrient fortified voluntarily by the manufacturer. Finally, the potentia=
l exists that some forms of nutrients used in food fortification are better=
 absorbed than those occurring in some natural forms; for example, the form=
 of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> used in RTEC is better absorbed than those forms=
 in meat or eggs<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref57" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref57" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>57</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. This underscores the effect that the bioavailability of nutri=
ents has on nutrient density.</p></section><section id=3D"sec1-7"><h3 class=
=3D"pmc_sec_title">7. Should the nutrient density of individual foods be co=
nsidered, or is it more important to consider the nutrient density of the e=
ntire diet?</h3>
<p>People do not eat individual foods alone; they either prepare mixed dish=
es, such as pastas, stews or casseroles, or serve a variety of foods at a s=
ingle meal or snack =E2=80=93 some of which may be nutrient dense, whereas =
others may not be. For example, with few exceptions, a fruit salad or veget=
able with no sugar or oils added would have a high nutrient density score; =
however, if an oil- or sugar-based dressing were added, would the food stil=
l be nutrient dense? Mixed dishes tend to have low nutrient density scores,=
 since they are made from both nutrient-dense and non-nutrient-dense foods;=
 during preparation, they often have SFA, sugars or Na added. Lasagne with =
meat, for example, has a WNDS of 2=C2=B79. Nutrient-dense foods in the lasa=
gne are the carrots, onions and celery; non-nutrient-dense foods, as define=
d by the DGA, include whole milk, commercial tomato paste (high in Na), ref=
ined-grain pasta, pancetta, wine, Parmesan cheese, ground meat and butter. =
Oils, especially heart-healthy olive oils, are also used; although these ar=
e not defined by the 2010 DGA as a nutrient-dense food, they do have a reco=
mmendation in the US Department of Agriculture meal patterns (27 g (5=C2=B7=
4 tsp) in a 8368 kJ (2000 kcal) diet). Can the nutrient density score be im=
proved without compromising the dish? To a degree: lean meat, low-Na tomato=
 paste, fat-free milk and whole-grain pasta can be used; also the amount of=
 cheese can be reduced. Vegetables, including aubergine and courgette, can =
also be added to the lasagne or can replace the pasta altogether. Will this=
 produce a similar menu item? Maybe not. Will this mixed dish be a truly nu=
trient-dense food? Probably not. Can it provide substantial amounts of nutr=
ients? Yes. Can the food fit into an overall healthy diet? Yes. Can the men=
u item be acceptable to consumers? It=E2=80=99s unclear, but it may be acce=
ptable to some consumers. Do consumers know how to prepare a more nutrient-=
dense version of this food and other mixed foods? It=E2=80=99s unclear, and=
 consumer education is likely needed.</p></section><section id=3D"sec1-8"><=
h3 class=3D"pmc_sec_title">8. What organization, institution or government =
agency will take up the task of defining nutrient density and nutrient-dens=
e foods?</h3>
<p>This depends on the ultimate use(s) of the nutrient profiling and the co=
untry involved. If nutrient profiling is to be used for regulatory purposes=
, appropriate agencies will need to be involved; for example, if the terms =
are to be used for food labels in the USA, the Food and Drug Administration=
 should be the agency to establish criteria. Consumer education uses could =
potentially involve consumer groups in conjunction with regulatory agencies=
 and industry. For advertising to children, the Institute of Medicine might=
 set the criteria<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref58" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref58" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>58</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, in collaboration with industry. If nutrient profiling is to b=
e used for other purposes, such as television advertising for children, oth=
er agencies might need to be involved. In Europe, the consensus of the Euro=
pean Union (EU) would be important.</p></section></section><section id=3D"s=
ec2"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"sec2"><a id=3D"sec2-anch=
or" data-anchor-id=3D"sec2" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>The perspective of the=
 European Union</h2>
<p>The issues about nutrient profiling of foods and the nutrient density of=
 foods confronting Europeans actually seem very similar to those we face in=
 the USA. Conditions for the EU-wide use of nutrition and health claims wer=
e set by the European Parliament and Council Regulation 1924/2006<sup>(</su=
p>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref59" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref59" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>59</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. In order to carry a claim, all foods and beverages had to hav=
e a favourable nutrient profile<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref59" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref59" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>59</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Nutrient profiles were to be based primarily on excessive con=
tent of disqualifying nutrients, salt, sugar and fat. Researchers and indus=
try were encouraged to develop nutrient profile models to provide a scienti=
fic basis for the regulation of health claims<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref59" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref59" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>59</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. This regulation gave the EU commission the =E2=80=98task to e=
stablish specific nutrient profiles, including exemptions, which foods or c=
ertain categories of foods must comply with in order to bear nutrition of h=
ealth claims and the conditions for the use of nutrition of health claims=
=E2=80=99. The goal was to restrict products considered to be unhealthy fro=
m making nutrition and health claims. However, the development of nutrient =
profiling systems, originally scheduled for 2009, has not been finalized du=
e to a lack of consensus and both internal and external opposition<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref60" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref60" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>60</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>One concern was that nutrient profiling would be used as reference by re=
gulators to tax or restrict the marketing and sale of =E2=80=98bad foods=E2=
=80=99. In 2010, members of the European Parliament voted to delete the nut=
rient profiling provision from the Nutrition and Health Claims Regulation f=
or the EU. With the European Parliament evenly split, nutrient profiling be=
came a political issue. At this time, there is still uncertainty about deve=
loping a pan-European nutrient profiling system, since any Commission initi=
ative in this area would need the approval of all twenty-seven EU member st=
ates<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref61" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref61" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>61</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>In the meantime, individual country jurisdictions, not to mention privat=
e industry, have been developing their own nutrient profiling systems. Amon=
g these are the SAIN,LIM system adopted by the French regulatory agency ANS=
ES<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref62" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref62" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>62</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and the FSA=E2=80=93Ofcom system developed for the correspondi=
ng regulatory agency in the UK<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref62" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref62" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>62</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. A recent study published in a peer-reviewed journal provided =
validations of nutrient profiling systems with respect to independently obt=
ained measures of a healthy diet<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref63" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref63" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>63</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>The technical concerns about the methodology of nutrient profiling are c=
omparable in the EU and in the USA. In 2006, representatives from nearly fi=
fteen different countries, attending an International Life Sciences Institu=
te Europe workshop, concluded that a =E2=80=98food category=E2=80=99 approa=
ch was better than an =E2=80=98across the board=E2=80=99 system for nutrien=
t profiling and that further studies were needed to identify the final list=
 of nutrients to be considered in nutrient profiling<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref9" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref9" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>9</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>The member states of the EU have dietary recommendations for nutrients, =
foods or dietary patterns that are consistent with health promotion and red=
uction of diet-related chronic disease<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref64" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref64" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>64</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref65" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref65" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>65</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. However, as seen in the USA, in Europe too there is confusion=
 as to what constitutes a healthy diet and what recommendations should be f=
or diets that support health. In particular, nutrient profiling systems nee=
d to balance scientific rigour and policy goals. Even in the absence of a n=
utrient profiling system, the European Commission approved only 222 health =
claims (listed in the EU online register) but rejected more than 1600. The =
work of the European Commission on nutrient profiling has resumed, although=
 no target date has been specified as yet.</p></section><section id=3D"sec3=
"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"sec3"><a id=3D"sec3-anchor"=
 data-anchor-id=3D"sec3" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>Apparent contradictions a=
nd inconsistencies in nutrient profiling systems</h2>
<p>There are some contradictions and inconsistencies when defining nutrient=
 density. It is also apparent that the nutrient density of foods varies dep=
ending on the standard =E2=80=98unit=E2=80=99 used in the definition. The c=
hallenge is to identify a standard unit that reflects a reasonable serving =
for some foods and is a concept that consumers can understand. The implicat=
ions of the 2010 DGA are that all fruits and vegetables with no added fat o=
r added sugar are nutrient dense. However, as seen above, this may not be t=
he case. From this commentary, fruits and vegetables vary in terms of their=
 nutrient density. Moreover, fruits and vegetables would attain higher nutr=
ient density scores if phytochemicals were considered in the nutrient densi=
ty definition.</p>
<p>Lean meats have been considered a nutrient-dense food because of the nut=
rient profile unique to this food group. However, lean meats still have rel=
atively high levels of SFA compared with other food groups. Moreover, some =
of the nutrients rich in lean meats, including vitamin B<sub>12</sub>, Fe a=
nd Zn, have not been typically considered in nutrient profiling systems. Th=
us, lean meats may be excluded as a nutrient-dense food group by virtue of =
the nutrient density definition. Ignoring or excluding a food group may hav=
e important nutritional implications in the diets of Americans. Further, al=
though there is an =E2=80=98official=E2=80=99 US Department of Agriculture =
definition of lean meat (the portion of total beef containing 9=C2=B728 g o=
f total fat or less per 100 g (after cooking))<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref66" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref66" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>66</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, it is unlikely that consumers are aware of it.</p>
<p>Another issue is that total energy content is not considered in most nut=
rient density definitions. Thus, foods that are both nutrient dense and ene=
rgy dense may pose some challenges when translating the nutrient density co=
ncept to consumers. It is unclear if this nutrient- and energy-dense concep=
t will be taken to another level of complexity in that they should be consu=
med in =E2=80=98moderation=E2=80=99. Finally, mixed dishes may be identifie=
d as nutrient dense yet one or more of the ingredients may be categorized a=
s non-nutrient dense when consumed alone.</p></section><section id=3D"sec4"=
><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"sec4"><a id=3D"sec4-anchor" =
data-anchor-id=3D"sec4" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>Potential unintended conse=
quences in using a nutrient density approach</h2>
<p>Nutrient-dense foods can also be energy dense<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref67" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref67" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>67</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref68" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref68" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>68</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. As Huth <em>et al</em>.<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref68" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref68" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>68</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> pointed out: =E2=80=98three of the top 10 sources of (kilo) ca=
lories (or kJ) and SFA (beef, milk and cheese) contribute 46=C2=B73 % of th=
e calcium, 49=C2=B75 % of the vitamin D, 42=C2=B73 % of the vitamin B<sub>1=
2</sub> as well as other essential nutrients to the American diet=E2=80=99.=
 Despite that these foods provide nearly one-half of Ca and vitamin D, iden=
tified by the 2010 DGA as nutrients of public health concern<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref3" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref3" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>3</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>, should these foods be eschewed because they are high in energ=
y and SFA? Nuts and avocados are other examples of nutrient-dense, energy-d=
ense foods that have been associated with diet and health benefits<sup>(</s=
up>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref53" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref53" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>53</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref54" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref54" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>54</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref69" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref69" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>69</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. Further, as stated previously, some food sources that are hig=
h in energy, added sugars and SFA make major contributions to dietary fibre=
 and micronutrients. Any dietary modifications that include reduction in en=
ergy, added sugars or SFA should consider such modifications so as not to i=
nduce the unintended consequence of lowering overall diet quality<sup>(</su=
p>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref68" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref68" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>68</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>Is it reasonable to assume that Americans will consume vegetables withou=
t added fats or Na? A study has shown that children will consume more bitte=
r flavoured vegetables, like broccoli, if they are served with a Ranch Dres=
sing<sup>=C2=AE</sup> flavoured dip<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref70" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref70" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>70</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. If the recommendation is to choose a lower-fat version of the=
 food, a low-fat dip may then add sugars or Na to the diet. With the dip, w=
ould the broccoli remain nutrient dense? Is it more important for children =
to consume nutrient-rich foods like broccoli, even at the expense of adding=
 sugars and Na to the diet?</p>
<p>Labelling foods as either nutrient dense or not may seem to consumers to=
 be a =E2=80=98good food=E2=80=93bad food=E2=80=99 approach. Promoting nutr=
ient-dense foods as =E2=80=98good foods=E2=80=99, without regard to energy =
content, could mislead the consumer into thinking they can eat as many or a=
s much of nutrient-dense foods as they want, which could result in energy i=
ntakes that exceed recommendations. Caution needs to be taken in applying n=
utrient density measures to individual foods rather than to total diets. La=
belling foods as =E2=80=98good foods=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98bad foods=E2=80=
=99 is inconsistent with a total diet approach and could cause people to ab=
andon efforts to make dietary improvements, leading to unhealthy eating hab=
its<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref71" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref71" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>71</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. The value of a food should be determined within the context o=
f the total diet<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref71" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref71" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>71</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. A focus on moderation and proportionality in the context of t=
he total diet, rather than on specific nutrients and foods, can help reduce=
 consumer confusion. It is the position of the Academy of Nutrition and Die=
tetics that =E2=80=98the total diet and overall pattern of food eaten is th=
e most important focus of a healthful eating style. All foods can fit withi=
n this pattern=E2=80=99<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref71" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref71" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>71</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>. It is important that consumer messaging regarding nutrient de=
nsity emphasizes a balance of foods, rather than any one food, within the c=
ontext of the total diet. Programmes such as the National Institutes of Hea=
lth=E2=80=99s National Heart, Blood, and Lung Institute=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98=
Go, Slow, Whoa=E2=80=99 classification<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref39" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref39" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>39</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and NuVal<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref72" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref72" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>72</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> come very close to =E2=80=98good food=E2=80=93bad food=E2=80=
=99 systems. Although these may be easy for consumers to understand, it can=
 also lead to omitting important foods from the diet.</p></section><section=
 id=3D"sec5"><h2 class=3D"pmc_sec_title" data-anchor-id=3D"sec5"><a id=3D"s=
ec5-anchor" data-anchor-id=3D"sec5" class=3D"usa-anchor"></a>Practical impl=
ications and conclusions</h2>
<p>The 2005 report of the Dietary Guidelines Advisory Committee<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref1" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref1" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>1</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and the EU have called for the development of a scientifically=
 valid definition for nutrient density and recommended that it would also b=
e useful on the food label so consumers can use it to make educated decisio=
ns about buying and consuming healthier foods. Developing a valid measure f=
or assessing the nutrient density of foods has the potential to assist cons=
umers in making more nutritious food choices. Understandably, a consumer ed=
ucation programme will be needed to demonstrate how to use the nutrient den=
sity measure within the concept of the total diet. Katz <em>et al</em>.<sup=
>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref7" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref7" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>7</sup>
</a>
<sup>,</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref10" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref10" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>10</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> and Glanz <em>et al.</em>
<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref73" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref73" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>73</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup> showed that using the Nutrient Rich Foods approach was effecti=
ve in improving the diet of consumers. Larger and longer studies are needed=
 to confirm the findings once a consensus has been reached on whether a nut=
rient dense score should be developed and validated for single foods or mor=
e broadly for assessing nutrient density of the total diet<sup>(</sup>
<a href=3D"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10282407/#ref71" class=
=3D"usa-link" aria-describedby=3D"ref71" aria-expanded=3D"false">
<sup>71</sup>
</a>
<sup>)</sup>.</p>
<p>Due to the difficulties in defining the concept of nutrient density, it =
seems ultimately that a real science-based definition may be unlikely due t=
o the inherent complexities and lack of answers to the unresolved questions=
. As a result, in addition to the outstanding scientifically relevant quest=
ions that need to be addressed in developing such a definition, it is imper=
ative to address whether consumers will understand and apply the concept of=
 the nutrient density approach. Essentially, will the application of a nutr=
ient density system be feasible, economical and culturally relevant to cons=
umers, and will it help consumers change behaviour that translates into mak=
ing wise food choices and consuming a healthier diet? Both the development =
of a standard nutrient density definition and the relevance to the consumer=
 will need to be considered equally for such an approach to translate into =
appropriate and effective dietary changes that will result in a healthier a=
nd sustainable eating pattern.</p></section><section id=3D"ack1" class=3D"a=
